    <subsection>
        <title>Identities and Inverses</title>

        <p>We will start with some definitions.</p>

        <p>The number <m>0</m> is called the <term>additive identity</term>. If the sum of two numbers is the additive identity, <m>0</m>, these two numbers are called <term>additive inverses</term>. For example, <m>2</m> is the additive inverse of <m>-2</m>, and the additive inverse of <m>-2</m> is <m>2</m>.</p>

        <p>Similarly, the number <m>1</m> is called the <term>multiplicative identity</term>. If the product of two numbers is the multiplicative identity, <m>1</m>, these two numbers are called <term>multiplicative inverses</term>. For example, <m>2</m> is the multiplicative inverse of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, and the multiplicative inverse of <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m> is <m>-\frac{3}{2}</m>. The multiplicative inverse is also called <term>reciprocal</term>.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Introduction to Algebraic Properties</title>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Commutative Property</title>

            <p>When we compute the area of a rectangle, we generally multiply the length by the width. Does the result change if we multiply the width by the length?</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Horizontal and Vertical Rectangles</caption>
                <image width="70%">
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[red,fill=yellow] (0,2) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,2) -- cycle; %horizontal
                                \node[below] at (2,0) {$4$ cm};
                                \node[right] at (4,1) {$2$ cm};
                                \node[] at (2,1) {$\text{Area}=4\cdot2=8$};
                            \draw[red,fill=yellow] (6,4) -- (6,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,4) -- cycle; %vertical
                                \node[right] at (6.5,-0.2) {$2$ cm};
                                \node[right] at (8.1,2) {$4$ cm};
                                \node[] at (7,2.05) {$\begin{aligned}\text{Area}\amp=2\cdot4\\\amp=8\end{aligned}$};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>We can see <m>4\cdot2=2\cdot4</m>. If we denote the length of a rectangle with <m>L</m> and the width with <m>W</m>, this implies <m>LW=WL</m>. This is referred to as the <term>commutative property of multiplication</term>.</p>

            <p>The commutative property also applies to addition, as in <m>1+2=2+1</m>, which is called the <term>commutative property of addition</term>. However, there is no commutative property of subtraction or division, as <m>2-1\ne1-2</m>, and <m>\frac{4}{2}\ne\frac{2}{4}</m>.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Associative Property</title>

            <p>Let's extend that example to a rectangular prism with length <m>L=4\text{ cm}</m>, width <m>W=3\text{ cm}</m>, and height <m>H=2\text{ cm}</m>. To compute the volume of this solid, we multiply the length, width and height, which we write as <m>LWH</m>.</p>

            <p>In the following figure, on the left side, we multiply the length and width first, and then multiply the height; on the right side, we multiply the width and height first, and then multiply the length. Let's compare the products.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="46% 46%"> 
                <figure>
                    <caption><m>(4\cdot3)\cdot2=24</m></caption>
                        <image>
                        <description>A rectangular prism with the side showing the length and the width highlighted.</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}%(x,z,y)
                                \node[white] at (2,0,0) {.};
                                \draw[red] (0,0,0) -- ++(-4,0,0) -- ++(0,-2,0) -- ++(4,0,0) -- cycle; %front face
                                \draw[red] (0,0,0) -- ++(0,0,-3) -- ++(0,-2,0) -- ++(0,0,3) -- cycle; %side
                                \draw[red,fill=yellow] (0,0,0) -- ++(-4,0,0) -- ++(0,0,-3) -- ++(4,0,0) -- cycle; %top
                                        \node[above] at (-2,0,0) {$L=4\text{ cm}$};
                                        \node[above,rotate=90] at (0,-1,0) {$H=2\text{ cm}$};
                                        \node[above,rotate=45] at (0,0,-1.5) {$W=3\text{ cm}$};
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure>
                    <caption><m>4\cdot(3\cdot2)=24</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>A rectangular prism with the side showing the width and the height highlighted.</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}%(x,z,y)
                                \node[white] at (2,0,0) {.};
                                \draw[red] (0,0,0) -- ++(-4,0,0) -- ++(0,-2,0) -- ++(4,0,0) -- cycle; %front face
                                \draw[red,fill=yellow] (0,0,0) -- ++(0,0,-3) -- ++(0,-2,0) -- ++(0,0,3) -- cycle; %side
                                \draw[red] (0,0,0) -- ++(-4,0,0) -- ++(0,0,-3) -- ++(4,0,0) -- cycle; %top
                                        \node[above] at (-2,0,0) {$L=4\text{ cm}$};
                                        \node[above,rotate=90] at (0,-1,0) {$H=2\text{ cm}$};
                                        \node[above,rotate=45] at (0,0,-1.5) {$W=3\text{ cm}$};
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

            <p>We can see <m>(LW)H=L(WH)</m>. This is known as the <term>associative property of multiplication</term>.</p>

            <p>The associative property also applies to addition, as in <m>(1+2)+3=1+(2+3)</m>, which is called the <term>associative property of addition</term>. However, there is no associative property of subtraction, as <m>(3-2)-1\ne3-(2-1)</m>.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Distributive Property</title>

            <p>The final property we'll explore is called the <term>distributive property</term>, which involves both multiplication and addition. To conceptualize this property, let's consider what happens if we buy 3 sets that each contain one apple and one loaf of bread. This will have the exact same total cost as if we'd bought 3 apples and 3 loaves of bread. We write this algebraically as<me>3(a+b)=3a+3b</me>Visually, we can see that it's just a means of re-grouping:<me>3(\text{&#127823;}+ \text{&#127838;}) = 3(\text{&#127823;})+ 3(\text{&#127838;})</me></p>
        </paragraphs>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Summary of Algebraic Properties</title>
        <p>Let <m>a,</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> represent real numbers, variables, or algebraic expressions. Then the following properties hold:</p>

        <list xml:id="list-algebraic-properties">
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="item-commutative-property-of-multiplication">
                        <title>Commutative Property of Multiplication:</title>
                        <p><m>a\cdot b=b\cdot a</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="item-associative-property-of-multiplication">
                        <title>Associative Property of Multiplication:</title>
                        <p><m>a\cdot(b\cdot c)=(a\cdot b)\cdot c</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="item-commutative-property-of-addition">
                        <title>Commutative Property of Addition:</title>
                        <p><m>a+b=b+a</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="item-associative-property-of-addition">
                        <title>Associative Property of Addition:</title>
                        <p><m>a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="item-distributive-property">
                        <title>Distributive Property:</title>
                        <p><m>a(b+c)=ab+ac</m></p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
        </list>

        <p>Let's practice these properties in the following exercises.</p>

