    <subsection>
        <title>Applying the Commutative, Associative, and Distributive Properties</title>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Like Terms</title>
            <p>One of the main ways that we will use the commutative, associative, and distributive properties is to simplify expressions. In order to do this, we need to recognize <term>like terms</term>. Two terms are considered <term>like terms</term> if they contain the same variable raised to the same exponent. Here's a table comparing like terms and non-like terms:</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <sidebyside>
            <tabular>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Like Terms</cell>
                    <cell>Non-Like Terms</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>7x,2x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>7x,7y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-5xy,\frac{1}{3}xy</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-5x^2,-4x</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>4y^3,y^3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3x,4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3,-10</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2xy,5y</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Combining Like Terms</title>

            <p>We combine like terms when we take <m>2a+3a</m> and write the result as <m>5a</m>. The formal process actually involves invoking the distributive property, as we obtain:<md>
                <mrow>2a+3a \amp=(2+3)a</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=5a</mrow>
            </md>In practice, it's helpful to think of this as having <m>2</m> of an object and then an additional <m>3</m> of that same object. In total, we then have <m>5</m> of that object.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Where possible, simplify the following expressions by combining like terms.<ol label="a." cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>6c+12c-5c</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-5q-3q</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-3x-5y+4x</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>2x-3y+4z</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>We will combine all three like terms: <m>6c</m>, <m>12c</m> and <m>-5c</m>:<md>
                        <mrow>6c+12c-5c \amp=18c-5c</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=13c</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will combine like terms <m>-5q</m> and <m>-3q</m>:<md>
                        <mrow>-5q-3q \amp=-8q</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will combine like terms <m>-5x</m> and <m>4x</m>:<md>
                        <mrow>-3x-5y+4x \amp=-3x+4x+(-5y)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=x-5y</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>The expression <m>2x-3y+4z</m> cannot be simplified as there are no like terms.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark>
            <p>The expression <m>x</m> represents <m>1x</m> and the expression <m>-x</m> represents <m>-1x</m>, but we don't write either the <q><m>1</m></q> or the <q><m>-1</m></q> as each is implied. However, it's helpful when combining like terms to remember that <m>x=1x</m> and <m>-x=-1x</m>.</p>
        </remark>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Adding Expressions</title>

            <p>When we add an expression like <m>4x-5</m> to an expression like <m>3x-7</m>, we write them as follows:<me>(4x-5)+(3x-7)</me>In order to remove the given sets of parentheses and apply the commutative property of addition, we will rewrite the subtraction operation as <q>adding the opposite</q>:<me>4x+(-5)+3x+(-7)</me>At this point we can apply the commutative property of addition and then combine like terms. Here's how the entire problem will look:<md>
                <mrow>(4x-5)+(3x-7)\amp=4x+(-5)+3x+(-7)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=4x+3x+(-5)+(-7)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=7x+(-12)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=7x-12</mrow>
            </md></p>
        </paragraphs>

        <remark>
            <p>Once we get more comfortable simplifying such expressions, we will simply write the following:<me>(4x-5)+(3x-7)=7x-12</me></p>
        </remark>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Use the associative, commutative, and distributive properties to simplify the following expressions as much as possible.<ol label="a.">
                    <li><p><m>(2x+3)+(4x+5)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>(-5x+3)+(4x-7)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>(-2x-1)+(-4x-9)</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>We will remove parentheses, and then combine like terms:<md>
                        <mrow>(2x+3)+(4x+5) \amp=2x+3+4x+5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=2x+4x+3+5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=6x+8</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will remove parentheses, and then combine like terms::<md>
                        <mrow>(-5x+3)+(4x-7)\amp=-5x+3+4x+(-7)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=7x+(-4)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=7x-4</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will remove parentheses, and then combine like terms:<md>
                        <mrow>(-2x-1)+(-4x-9) \amp=-2x+(-1)+(-4x)+(-9)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-2x+(-4x)+(-1)+(-9)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-6x+(-10)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-6x-10</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Applying the Distributive Property with Negative Coefficients</title>

            <p>Applying the distributive property in an expression such as <m>2(3x+4)</m> is fairly straightforward, in that this becomes <m>2(3x)+2(4)</m> which we then simplify to <m>6x+8</m>. Applying the distributive property is a little trickier when subtraction or a negative constant is involved, for example, with the expression <m>2(3x-4)</m>. Recalling that subtraction is defined as <q>adding the opposite,</q> we can change the subtraction of positive <m>4</m> to the addition of negative <m>4</m>:<me>2\big(3x+(-4)\big)</me>Now when we distribute, we obtain:<me>2(3x)+2(-4)</me>As a final step, we see that this simplifies to:<me>6x-8</me></p>
        </paragraphs>

        <remark>
            <p>We can also extend the distributive property to one involving subtraction, which states that <m>a(b-c)=ab-ac</m>. With this property, we would simplify <m>2(3x-4)</m> more efficiently:<md>
                <mrow>2(3x-4) \amp=2(3x)-2(4)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=6x-8</mrow>
            </md>In general, we will use this approach.</p>
        </remark>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Apply the distributive property to each expression and simplify it as much as possible.<ol label="a." cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>-3(5x+7)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>2(-4x-1)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-4(2x-3)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-7(-x-9)</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>We will distribute <m>-3</m> into the parentheses:<md>
                        <mrow>-3(5x+7)\amp=-3(5x)+(-3)(7)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-15x-21</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will distribute <m>2</m> into the parentheses:<md>
                        <mrow>2(-4x-1)\amp=2(-4x)-2(1)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-8x-2</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will distribute <m>-4</m> into the parentheses:<md>
                        <mrow>-4(2x-3)\amp=-4(2x)-(-4)(3)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-8x+12</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>We will distribute <m>-7</m> into the parentheses:<md>
                        <mrow>-7(-x-9)\amp=-7(-x)-(-7)(9)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=7x+63</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

