                        <p>Let's look at what happens when we try to simplify <m>\left(x^2\right)^3</m>. If we write this out entirely with <m>x</m>, we have<md>
                            <mrow>\left(x^2\right)^3 \amp=\left(x^2\right)\left(x^2\right)\left(x^2\right)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=(x\cdot x)(x \cdot x) (x \cdot x)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=x\cdot x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=x^6</mrow>
                        </md>Note that to determine how many times <m>x</m> appeared as a factor (simply by multiplying this out), we see that we obtained the exponent of <m>6</m> by multiplying <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>Let's look at what happens when we try to simplify <m>(xy)^2</m>. If we write this out entirely with <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we have<md>
                            <mrow>(xy)^2 \amp=(xy)(xy)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=x \cdot y \cdot x \cdot y</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=x \cdot x \cdot y \cdot y</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=x^2y^2</mrow>
                        </md>Note that to determine how many times <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> appear as a factors (simply by counting this out and rearranging), the exponent on <m>xy</m> can simply be applied to both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <list xml:id="list-rules-of-exponents">
            <title>Summary of the Rules of Exponents</title>
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="item-product-to-sum-exponent-rule">
                    <title>Product of Powers</title>
                    <p><m>x^m\cdot x^n=x^{m+n}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="item-exponent-on-an-exponent-rule">
                    <title>Power to Power</title>
                    <p><m>(x^m)^n=x^{m\cdot n}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="item-exponent-on-a-product-rule">
                    <title>Product to Power</title>
                    <p><m>(xy)^n = x^n\cdot y^n</m></p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </list>

